        "materials_required": [
            "Raspberry Pi 3",
            "Micro SD card 16GB",
            "Arduino NANO or its compatible board",
            "Level converter (Between Arduino 5V and Pi 3.3V)",
            "USB camera with microphone (Logitech C270 used here)",
            "Servo motors: SG90 x 2",
            "Motor driver: L298N",
            "DC motors: 2 small DC motors  for hobby (Preferably 0.1uF capacitors attached)",
            "Gearbox: Transmit 2 motors to 2 wheels (reduction ratio 344.2:1 selected here)",
            "Wheels: 2 wheels attached to the shafts of Gearbox",
            "Caster wheel: The third wheel of robot",
            "Plate: Body of robot",
            "Battery(1): Supply DC 5V with enough current for Pi 3 and Arduino",
            "Battery(2): Supply DC 5V for 2 DC motors and 2 servos",
            "Jumper cables",
            "Solderless Breadboard",
            "USB cables: For power supply",
            "Orange-colored Ball: Target"
        ],
        "description": "This project details how to build a Pointer Dog Robot that uses a Raspberry Pi and Arduino to follow voice commands, trace a target, and point towards it autonomously.",
        "steps": [
            "Set up the Raspberry Pi with Raspbian Stretch using NOOBS on a 16GB micro SD card, connect to the internet, and update the system.",
            "Connect a USB camera with a microphone to the Raspberry Pi.",
            "Install OpenCV on the Raspberry Pi and download sample code for color tracking.",
            "Build a 2-axis platform for the camera using two servo motors, attaching the camera vertically.",
            "Configure the Arduino NANO to control the camera platform servos using UART communication with the Raspberry Pi.",
            "Install the Julius speech analyzer on the Raspberry Pi to process voice commands.",
            "Set up the audio input for Julius and test the microphone.",
            "Download and test a special dictionary for Julius containing the robot's command words.",
            "Connect additional wires for the drive motors, motor driver, and power supply.",
            "Activate the robot by running Julius in module mode, along with Python scripts for voice control and robot decision-making, in separate terminal windows.",
            "Command the robot with voice commands like 'Go Go', 'Back Back', 'Right Right', 'Left Left', and 'Ma-Te Ma-Te'.",
            "Make the robot track a target autonomously with the command 'Track Start' and stop tracking with 'Stay Down'."
        ]
